First M87 Event Horizon Telescope Results.¶

IV. Imaging the Central Supermassive Black Hole¶

Received 2019 February 11; revised 2019 March 5; accepted 2019 March 6; published 2019 April 10

We present the first Event Horizon Telescope (EHT) images of M87, using observations from April 2017 at 1.3 mm wavelength. These images show a prominent ring with a diameter of ~40 as, consistent with the size and shape of the lensed photon orbit encircling the "shadow" of a supermassive black hole. The ring is persistent across four observing nights and shows enhanced brightness in the south. To assess the reliability of these results, we implemented a two-stage imaging procedure. In the first stage, four teams, each blind to the others' work, produced images of M87 using both an established method (CLEAN) and a newer technique (regularized maximum likelihood). This stage allowed us to avoid shared human bias and to assess common features among independent reconstructions. In the second stage, we reconstructed synthetic data from a large survey of imaging parameters and then compared the results with the corresponding ground truth images. This stage allowed us to select parameters objectively to use when reconstructing images of M87....

The four teams

Fundamentals¶

Basics¶

  • two reciprocal spaces
    • time / frequency
    • space / spacial frequency
    • xyz / hkl
    • cm / cm$^{-1}$
  • regular sampling
    • of the time domain $\Delta t$
    • Nyquist-Shannon theorem : fastest correctly detected frequency is $F_{max} = \frac{1}{2 \Delta t}$
    • faster frequencies are aliased into the $[0..F_{max}]$
  • for an acquisition of $N$ point regularly sampled in time
    • as FT is in place, the spectral width $[0..F_{max}]$ is also sampled on $N$ point, with $\Delta F = \frac{F_{max}}{N}$
    • naturally, the total acquisition time is $T_{max} = N \Delta t$
    • combining the two, it comes $\Delta F = \frac{1}{2 T_{max}}$
  • for a signal observed during a limited time $T_{max}$, the resolution in frequency $\sigma_F$ is limited by the Gabor limit : $\sigma_F \gtrsim \frac 1 {4 \pi T_{max}}$
  • pairs of functions

slightly more involved¶

  • convolution

Periodisation¶

To work with a computer we have to sample the data.

Sampling is equivalent to multiplying the continuous signal by a set of $\delta$ function located periodically. This is called the $$ function (Sha a cyrilic letter). The FT of $$ with splitting $\Delta t$ is a $$ with splitting $\frac{1}{\Delta t}$. So the effect of sampling the continuous time domain signal is to periodisation of the continuous spectrum, and this explains the aliasing effect.

If we want a sampled spectrum as well, we have to multiply it by $$ with splitting $\Delta F$ which in turns implies the periodisation of the time domain by $\frac{1}{\Delta F}$

$\Rightarrow$ the DFT (Digital Fourier Transform), because it works on digitalized data always assumes a periodisation of the frequency AND time domain data.

apodisation and artefacts¶

Artefacts are inherent to FT

Apodisation consists multiplying the time domain data by a function to reduce these artefacts.

def slide_apod(zm=zm1):
    (fig, ax) = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=2)
    dd = d.copy().zf(4).display(figure=ax[0,0], title='transient')
    dd.rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz').display(zoom=zm,figure=ax[0,1], title='spectrum')
    dd = d.copy().apod_sin(0.5).zf(4).display(figure=ax[1,0], label='sine bell')
    dd.rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz').display(zoom=zm,figure=ax[1,1])
    dd = d.copy().hamming().zf(4).display(figure=ax[2,0], label='hamming')
    dd.rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz').display(zoom=zm,figure=ax[2,1])
    dd = d.copy().hanning().zf(4).display(figure=ax[3,0], label='hanning')
    dd.rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz').display(zoom=zm,figure=ax[3,1])
def slide_apod2(zm=zm2):
    dd = d.copy().zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')
    dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm,label='None', title='Comparing apodisations')
    for apod in ['apod_sin(0.5)','hamming()','hanning()']:
        dd = eval("d.copy().%s.zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')"%apod)
        dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm, new_fig=False, label=apod)
def slide_apod2b(zm=zm2):
    dd = d.copy().apod_sin(0.5).zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')
    dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm,label='apod_sin', title='Kaiser apodisations',mpldic={"linestyle":(0,(1,1))})
    for apod in ['hamming()']:
        dd = eval("d.copy().%s.zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')"%apod)
        dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm, new_fig=False, label=apod, mpldic={"linestyle":(0,(1,1))})
    for apod in ['kaiser(2.6)','kaiser(4)','kaiser(5.5)']:
        dd = eval("d.copy().%s.zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')"%apod)
        dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm, new_fig=False, label=apod)
def slide_apod3(zm=zm2):
    ds = d.copy().chsize(16*1024).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')
    ds.mult(1/ds.absmax).display(zoom=zm, title='sliding apodisation')
    for n in [2, 2.5, 3, 3.5, 4]:
        dd = d.copy().chsize(int(n*1024)).chsize(16*1024).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')
        dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm,new_fig=False)
#        ds += n*dd
def slide_apod3b(zm=zm2):
    global ds
    ds = d.copy().kaiser(2).zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')
    ds.mult(1/ds.absmax).display(zoom=zm, title='sliding apodisation')
    for n in [2.5, 3, 3.5, 4, 4.5]:
        dd = d.copy().kaiser(n).zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('Hz')
        dd.mult(1/dd.absmax).display(zoom=zm,new_fig=False)
        ds += n*dd

def real1(trunc=None):
    d = Apex.Import_1D('files/FTICR-Files/ESI_pos_Ubiquitin_000006.d')
    zm1 = (714.2,715.5)
    zm1b = (714.7, 714.75)
    zm2 = (1223.5, 1225.5)
    zm2b= (1224.45, 1224.6)
    if trunc: d.chsize(trunc)
    (fig,ax) = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2)
    d1=d.copy().hamming().zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('m/z').display(zoom=zm1, label='Ham', figure=ax[0,0])
    d2=d.copy().kaiser(2.5).zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('m/z').mult(0.9).display(zoom=zm1, figure=ax[0,0], label='kaiser')
    d1.display(zoom=zm1b, figure=ax[0,1])
    d2.display(zoom=zm1b, figure=ax[0,1])
    d3=d.copy().hamming().zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('m/z').display(zoom=zm2, label='Ham', figure=ax[1,0])
    d4=d.copy().kaiser(2.5).zf(4).rfft().modulus().set_unit('m/z').mult(0.9).display(zoom=zm2, figure=ax[1,0], label='kaiser')
    d3.display(zoom=zm2b, figure=ax[1,1])
    d4.display(zoom=zm2b, figure=ax[1,1])

Phasing¶

FT is instrinsically complex

Some remarks¶

  • all spectra so far were in modulus ( .modulus() )
  • phase of a line is equivalent to starting point of the signal
  • phase of each line accumulates at their respective frequency as soon as they are excited $\Rightarrow$ phase dependence linear with frequency
  • because of swept pulse, each line starts at a different moment during the pulse $\Rightarrow$ phase dependence quadratic with frequency
  • each line in the spectrum has a phase $\phi$, function of the frequency of the line $\phi(f)$ $$ \phi(f) \propto \phi_o + a f + b f^2 $$
  • but phase is defined only on $[0..2\pi]$ so there is no continuity $\Rightarrow$ tricky to correct
In [129]:
d = Solarix.Import_1D("/DATA/Phasage FTICR/cyto_C phased/cytoC_ms_000001.d").apod_sq_sin(0.1).zf(4).rfft().set_unit('m/z')
dap = Solarix.Import_1D("/DATA/Phasage FTICR/cyto_C phased/cytoC_ms_000001.d").apod_sq_sin(0.35).zf(4).rfft().set_unit('m/z')
def ph(ex, apod=False):
    if apod:
        dd = dap
    else:
        dd = d
    (fig, ax) = plt.subplots(nrows=2,ncols=1,sharex=True)
    dz = dd.copy().set_unit('m/z').extract(ex[0],ex[1]).display(figure=ax[0])
    dz = dd.copy().set_unit('m/z').extract(ex[0],ex[1]).phase(ex[3],ex[4]).apmin().display(figure=ax[1])

some examples¶

In [119]:
ph((1168,1172,1438.011050,241.250000,905.000000))

In addition¶

because of the width of the dispersive part is (much) wider than the absorptive part, the phase rotation of the dispersive part can "walk" on the absorptive part of the line nearby, and thus appear in the phased spectrum.

This shows up as a strong negative baseline.

In [120]:
ph((584,586,694.202733,125.000000,3742.076883))

The effect is stronger at low masses (high frequency $\Rightarrow$ fast phase rotation)

In [127]:
ph((390,392,460.252428,170.000000,12654.099460))
plt.xlim(xmin = 390.10, xmax=390.35); plt.ylim(ymin = -1E8, ymax=2E8);

On these examples, a very mild apodisation was used, in order keep the line shape as natural as possible.

The baseline effect can be reduced by applying a somewhat stronger apodisation, with some other artifacts appearing:

  • more noise
  • sharp negative wings on the sides of the peaks
In [130]:
ph((390,392,460.252428,170.000000,12654.099460), apod=True)
